{
  "doc_id": "18109",
  "text": "The thiamine concentration is known to be lower in patients with established risk factors than in those without such risk factors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Concentrations were also low among patients with chronic heart failure or hypoalbuminemia in our current study, and hospitalization for infectious diseases caused thiamine depletion, even in cases of adequate food intake. These findings suggest that universal supplementation of thiamine is unnecessary for elderly patients with infectious diseases on admission, and thiamine supplementation should be considered for elderly patients with risk factors for a low thiamine concentration during inpatient care for infectious diseases.",
